---
import ArchitectureComparison from "../../../components/ArchitectureComparison.astro";
import Community from "../../../components/Community.astro";
import CurrentArchitectureDiagram from "../../../components/EnterpriseArchitectureDiagram.astro";
import Nav from "../../../components/Nav.astro";
import Base from "../../../layouts/Base.astro";

const title = "Enterprise architecture roadmap: local-first — ChunkHound";
const description =
    "Why organizations reach for a central server, and the phased roadmap for solving those pain points in the local-only model.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description} type="article">
    <Nav currentPath={Astro.url.pathname} />

    <main>
        <header class="hero">
            <div class="container hero-inner">
                <p class="eyebrow">Enterprise roadmap</p>
                <h1>
                    The pressure to centralize is a symptom.<br /><span
                        >The cure is a better DB.</span>
                </h1>
                <p class="hero-lead">
                    ChunkHound is local-only by design. The database is where
                    the friction lives: it is large, slow to build, and requires
                    source alongside it. Organizations naturally look at a
                    server to solve these problems. Our thesis: fix the DB
                    itself, and the server isn't needed. This page names each
                    friction point, then shows the phased roadmap for removing
                    it.
                </p>
                <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Page links">
                    <a class="button primary" href="#why-centralize"
                        >Why centralize?</a
                    >
                    <a class="button secondary" href="#roadmap">The roadmap</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </header>

        <section class="page-section" aria-labelledby="current-title">
            <div class="container">
                <p class="eyebrow">Current architecture</p>
                <h2 id="current-title">The product is local-first</h2>
                <p class="section-lead">
                    A local process owns the project database and keeps it
                    current. External embedding, reranking, or LLM providers are
                    optional dependencies—not a ChunkHound server. A server or
                    CI job can also copy a pre-indexed DB, run the local process
                    against it using the native HTTP MCP transport
                    (<code>--transport http</code>), and then stop; that remains
                    local-first at the workload boundary.
                </p>
                <CurrentArchitectureDiagram />
            </div>
        </section>

        <section
            id="why-centralize"
            class="page-section alt-section"
            aria-labelledby="gaps-title"
        >
            <div class="container">
                <p class="eyebrow">Why organizations centralize</p>
                <h2 id="gaps-title">The database is the bottleneck</h2>
                <p class="section-lead">
                    Every reason we hear for wanting a central ChunkHound server
                    traces back to friction with the database. Here are the most
                    common ones.
                </p>

                <div class="gap-grid">
                    <article class="gap-card">
                        <span class="gap-number">1</span>
                        <h3>DBs require a source checkout</h3>
                        <p>
                            Today the DB lives inside a project clone.
                            Non-developers cannot use ChunkHound without
                            checking out code they do not need, and CI workflows
                            must carry the entire repository alongside the
                            index.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                    <article class="gap-card">
                        <span class="gap-number">2</span>
                        <h3>DB artifacts are too large</h3>
                        <p>
                            An uncompressed project index can be several
                            gigabytes. Distributing it to every developer or CI
                            runner is expensive and slow. Organizations assume a
                            server must own the data so clients do not have to.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                    <article class="gap-card">
                        <span class="gap-number">3</span>
                        <h3>Indexing is slow</h3>
                        <p>
                            Each developer indexes from scratch or
                            incrementally. Python-level bottlenecks (file
                            scanning, chunking, vector index builds) make a
                            central service that indexes once and serves many
                            feel like the obvious fix.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                    <article class="gap-card">
                        <span class="gap-number">4</span>
                        <h3>No central upgrade or distribution</h3>
                        <p>
                            There is no mechanism today to push a fresh DB to
                            every machine, roll back a bad one, or notify users
                            of an available upgrade. Teams manage this manually
                            or skip it.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                    <article class="gap-card">
                        <span class="gap-number">5</span>
                        <h3>No central policy or audit</h3>
                        <p>
                            Every DB is fully local. Organizations that need
                            request-time enforcement or an audit trail see a
                            central query service as the natural authorization
                            boundary.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section
            id="roadmap"
            class="page-section"
            aria-labelledby="roadmap-title"
        >
            <div class="container">
                <p class="eyebrow">Roadmap</p>
                <h2 id="roadmap-title">Solving what tempts centralization</h2>
                <p class="section-lead">
                    Each gap above has a fix in the local-only model. The phases
                    below show what ships when. After Phase 2 the common reasons
                    for a server are gone; Phase 3 addresses the remaining edge
                    cases.
                </p>

                <div class="phase-list">
                    <article class="phase-card shipped">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Shipped</span>
                        <h3>Rust-native file scanner</h3>
                        <p>
                            Directory scanning now uses a Rust extension built
                            on the <code>ignore</code>
                            crate's parallel walker, replacing <code
                                >os.walk</code
                            >. First increment of a broader Rust-native
                            pipeline.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gap 3 — faster file scanning.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card shipped">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Shipped</span>
                        <h3>DB auto-compaction</h3>
                        <p>
                            DuckDB databases auto-compact via atomic swap when
                            fragmentation crosses a configurable threshold.
                            Solved what used to be hundreds of GBs of bloat,
                            bringing DBs down to single-digit GBs.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gap 2 — reclaims disk space from
                            fragmentation with no indexing downtime.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card in-progress">
                        <span class="phase-badge">In progress</span>
                        <h3>Rust pipeline rewrite — operating at max speed</h3>
                        <p>
                            <a
                                href="https://github.com/chunkhound/chunkhound/pull/375"
                                >PR #375</a
                            >
                            (Phase 0 Rust DB writer) already proves the direction:
                            cumulative 4.4x speedup on 4000 files by replacing Python
                            per-file DB writes with native Rust batch operations,
                            direct PyO3 extraction (no JSON serialization), and an
                            HNSW bookend protocol (drop once before writes, rebuild
                            once after). The end goal: CH infra is no longer the bottleneck
                            — indexing runs at the speed of the embeddings provider.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gap 3 — operating the underlying
                            DB and HNSW at max throughput, eliminating Python overhead
                            from the hot path.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card future">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Future</span>
                        <h3>LSM-Vec: concurrent in-place index building</h3>
                        <p>
                            Plan to integrate <a
                                href="https://github.com/el-yawd/lsm-vec"
                                >LSM-Vec</a
                            >, an embedded Rust vector index whose LSM-tree
                            design supports true in-place efficient updates —
                            unlike HNSW and IVF which need full rebuilds or
                            expensive incremental segment management. This lets
                            index building run concurrently with the ingestion
                            pipeline instead of blocking at the end, further
                            optimizing overall indexing time.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gap 3 — eliminates the blocking
                            index build phase. Index stays current incrementally as
                            chunks arrive.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card future">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Future</span>
                        <h3>Self-contained DBs</h3>
                        <p>
                            Audit and fix all code paths that assume source
                            files are available alongside the DB. Replace with
                            chunk data from the index. The current chunking
                            algorithm applies chunk overlaps, so reconstruction
                            must account for that carefully.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gap 1. Non-developers and CI
                            can use the DB without a repository clone.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card future">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Future</span>
                        <h3>DB split/merge for independent indexing</h3>
                        <p>
                            Split and merge DBs to index individual repos
                            independently, then combine into one unified
                            artifact for distribution. Shopware's use case:
                            index each microservice repo separately, merge
                            into a single searchable DB. This also enables
                            horizontally scalable indexing — a centralized CI
                            can index repos in parallel across machines, then
                            merge into one artifact.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gaps 1 and 4 — no source
                            checkout needed on consuming side; enables
                            automated CI distribution pipelines without a
                            central server.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card future">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Future</span>
                        <h3>Artifact optimization + auto-distribution</h3>
                        <p>
                            Compress text chunks via DB-level compression; ship
                            baselines without the vector index and let clients
                            build vector index locally; shard the DB by paths or
                            semantic units with partial updates building on
                            join/split. Combined with auto-distribution (CI
                            publishes once, clients pull incrementally).
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gaps 2 and 4.
                        </p>
                    </article>

                    <article class="phase-card future">
                        <span class="phase-badge">Future</span>
                        <h3>Permission-aware merge and distribution pipeline</h3>
                        <p>
                            Permissions are handled at the object store level.
                            The store integrates with the org's identity
                            provider — if you can access the artifact, you also
                            have access to the source repo. The constraint
                            shifts to the merge pipeline: don't combine repos
                            into one artifact when consumers may only be
                            authorized for a subset. Distribution must respect
                            per-repo access boundaries.
                        </p>
                        <p class="phase-gaps">
                            <strong>Solves:</strong> gap 5. No central query
                            service, no separate policy system — permissions
                            inherit from the object store's existing ACLs.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                </div>

                <aside class="timeline-note">
                    <strong>What about the server alternative?</strong>
                    Centralizing means either delegating to a distributed vector DB
                    (ChromaDB, LanceDB, Qdrant — with their ops, sharding, replication
                    overhead) or re-solving every bottleneck above in a server context.
                    The LSM-Vec roadmap is the opposite: solve each bottleneck at
                    the embedded library level so the local model needs nothing a
                    developer doesn't already run locally.
                </aside>
                <aside class="timeline-note" style="margin-top: var(--space-3)">
                    <strong>Already available</strong> — ChunkHound ships a native HTTP MCP
                    transport (<code>--transport http</code>). Same binary, no external proxy.
                    Full server trade-offs documented in the comparison table below.
                </aside>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section
            class="page-section alt-section"
            aria-labelledby="index-maintenance-title"
        >
            <div class="container">
                <p class="eyebrow">The hidden server cost</p>
                <h2 id="index-maintenance-title">
                    A live central index is a distributed database problem
                </h2>
                <p class="section-lead">
                    A local copy periodically receives a published baseline,
                    then maintains one branch or revision with incremental
                    indexing. A central service must keep every queryable branch
                    fresh to a tighter shared-view target while serving reads.
                    HNSW and IVF indexes can accept some incremental writes, but
                    deletes, retraining, compaction, and rebuilds require a
                    growing/sealed segment strategy and background capacity.
                    Production vector systems use WALs, segments, tombstones,
                    replicas, and shard-level maintenance to manage this
                    lifecycle.
                </p>
                <div class="index-maintenance-grid">
                    <article>
                        <h3>Local copy with embedded index</h3>
                        <p>
                            Periodically publish a self-contained DB baseline to
                            object storage. Thin manager checks for fresh
                            versions, verifies, activates. The roadmap's LSM-Vec
                            backend keeps vectors on disk and graph edges in an
                            LSM-tree, avoiding all-in-memory HNSW rebuilds. A
                            server or CI job can copy, query, proxy MCP, and
                            exit.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                    <article>
                        <h3>Central live corpus</h3>
                        <p>
                            Ingest all repositories and branches, route queries
                            across shards, merge results, rebuild or compact
                            indexes, replicate data, and preserve freshness
                            during failures. A central operator must also manage
                            a distributed vector DB (ChromaDB, LanceDB, Qdrant)
                            with its own cluster lifecycle, capacity, backups,
                            and incident response.
                        </p>
                    </article>
                </div>
                <aside class="index-scale-note">
                    <strong>Scale asymmetry:</strong> local-first targets at most
                    roughly 10M vectors per client. The current 256-dimensional envelope
                    is about 30–40 GB per client, with further compression still needed.
                    The ~100M-vector figure describes a centralized aggregate across
                    multiple branches—not one local copy. The server must store the
                    branch permutations or execute dynamic cross-DB joins, in addition
                    to index, metadata, replica, backup, and rebuild costs.
                    <span class="source-links">
                        See <a
                            href="https://github.com/facebookresearch/faiss/wiki/Faiss-indexes"
                            >FAISS</a
                        >,
                        <a
                            href="https://docs.weaviate.io/weaviate/concepts/vector-index"
                            >Weaviate</a
                        >,
                        <a
                            href="https://qdrant.tech/documentation/concepts/storage/"
                            >Qdrant</a
                        >, and <a href="https://github.com/el-yawd/lsm-vec"
                            >LSM-Vec (LSM-tree-based vector index)</a
                        >.
                    </span>
                </aside>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="page-section" aria-labelledby="comparison-title">
            <div class="container">
                <p class="eyebrow">Trade-offs</p>
                <h2 id="comparison-title">Every dimension, side by side</h2>
                <ArchitectureComparison />
            </div>
        </section>

        <section
            id="discuss"
            class="page-section alt-section"
            aria-labelledby="discuss-title"
        >
            <div class="container narrow">
                <p class="eyebrow">Discussion</p>
                <h2 id="discuss-title">
                    This is a roadmap, not a manifesto.<br />
                    <span>Challenge it.</span>
                </h2>

                <aside class="validation-callout">
                    <h3>Open questions we're still working through</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            Is the Rust pipeline rewrite or LSM-Vec the bigger
                            lever for indexing speed?
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Should the merged DB artifact preserve per-repo
                            shard boundaries, or rely on the object store for
                            access control?
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Can DB compression alone make artifact sizes small
                            enough to skip shipping without the vector index?
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Does the object store permission model scale to
                            orgs with thousands of repos and fine-grained
                            team access?
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                        This roadmap is shaped by real production constraints.
                        If you see a flaw, a missing gap, or a better path —
                        open an issue or PR. We'd rather be wrong early than
                        build the wrong thing.
                    </p>
                </aside>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>

    <Community />
</Base>

<style>
    .hero {
        padding: var(--space-10) 0;
        border-bottom: var(--border-w-subtle) solid var(--border-subtle);
    }

    .narrow {
        max-width: 880px;
    }
    .hero-inner {
        max-width: 1000px;
    }
    .eyebrow,
    .phase-badge {
        color: var(--text-tertiary);
        font-size: var(--text-xs);
        font-weight: 600;
        letter-spacing: 0.12em;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    }
    .hero .eyebrow {
        margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
        color: var(--primary);
    }
    h1 {
        max-width: 900px;
        color: var(--text-primary);
        font-size: var(--text-4xl);
        line-height: var(--lh-4xl);
        letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    }
    h1 span {
        color: var(--primary);
    }
    .hero-lead {
        max-width: 780px;
        margin-top: var(--space-5);
        color: var(--text-secondary);
        font-size: var(--text-lg);
        line-height: var(--lh-lg);
    }
    .hero-actions {
        display: flex;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
        gap: var(--space-3);
        margin-top: var(--space-7);
    }
    .button {
        display: inline-flex;
        min-height: var(--target-lg);
        padding: 0 var(--space-6);
        align-items: center;
        justify-content: center;
        border: var(--border-w-default) solid var(--border-color);
        border-radius: var(--radius-md);
        font-size: var(--text-sm);
        font-weight: 600;
        text-decoration: none;
    }
    .button:focus-visible {
        outline: var(--border-w-emphasis) solid var(--link-focus);
        outline-offset: 3px;
    }
    .button:hover {
        text-decoration: none;
    }
    .button.primary {
        border-color: var(--primary);
        color: var(--on-primary);
        background: var(--primary);
    }
    .button.secondary {
        color: var(--text-primary);
        background: var(--bg-surface);
    }
    .page-section {
        padding: var(--space-10) 0;
        scroll-margin-top: var(--target-xl);
    }
    .alt-section {
        border-block: var(--border-w-subtle) solid var(--border-subtle);
        background: var(--bg-surface);
    }

    h2 {
        color: var(--text-primary);
        font-size: var(--text-2xl);
        line-height: var(--lh-2xl);
        font-weight: 600;
    }
    h3 {
        color: var(--text-primary);
        font-size: var(--text-lg);
        line-height: var(--lh-lg);
    }
    .section-lead {
        max-width: 820px;
        margin-top: var(--space-4);
        color: var(--text-secondary);
        font-size: var(--text-base);
        line-height: var(--lh-base);
    }
    .gap-grid {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr));
        gap: var(--space-4);
        margin-top: var(--space-7);
    }
    .gap-card {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        gap: var(--space-2);
        padding: var(--space-5);
        border: var(--border-w-default) solid var(--border-color);
        border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
        background: var(--bg-page);
    }
    .gap-card p {
        color: var(--text-secondary);
        font-size: var(--text-sm);
        line-height: var(--lh-sm);
    }
    .gap-number {
        color: var(--primary);
        font-size: var(--text-2xl);
        font-weight: 700;
        line-height: 1;
    }
    .phase-list {
        display: grid;
        gap: var(--space-5);
        margin-top: var(--space-7);
    }
    .phase-card {
        padding: var(--space-6);
        border: var(--border-w-default) solid var(--border-color);
        border-radius: var(--radius-xl);
        background: var(--bg-page);
    }
